<font color="#FF0000">MEMORIAL DAY</font><br>
<tt>Sun May 25 13:23:11 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To All,<br>
     Dick is 100% correct.  I'm glad he brought it up.  It certainly alarms me when this society moves holidays to a Monday to create a three day weekend.  What does this teach the children of this nation?  It's better to have a three day weekend than to honor a day?  I know someone who works for United Parcel Service (UPS) and he told me they (the company is even contemplating even  giving the first Monday of July off as the Independence Day holiday rather than July 4th which falls in the middle of the week many times.  They figure the holiday is better used as a three day weekend during the summer.  Imagine, not even recognizing July 4th, our independence day and the birthday of this nation for the sake of a three day weekend.  Is anything sacred?  As a teacher, I will be sure to honor our fallen soldiers with my students on the true Memorial Day.<br><br>
The one great thing is that we now have a moment of silence, thanks to TNT.  I guess what matters is that Americans remember the fallen soldiers.  Too bad for many, it is only for one day in May and one day in November. 
